Sliding Window Pattern - This helps us in finding sub arrays or substrings that meet specific criteria.
In this case the continuous subsets of elements are processed or analyzed.

Sliding window means we take a range (window) of elements, process it, and then slide it forward instead of recalculating everything again.

Imagine:

You are checking 5 consecutive students' marks
Instead of recalculating sum every time,
You:
➕ add next student
➖ remove previous student
👉 That’s sliding window

Key rule for identifying Sliding Window pattern :-
Sliding window works when:
- The problem deals with contiguous sub-arrays/substrings
- You can expand/shrink window and maintain validity

The key approach to solve sliding window problems is:
- Use two pointers to represent the window's start and end
- For every iteration, increment the right pointer get the new element and do the computation
- Then increment the left pointer to shrink the window (remove the leftmost element) and do the computation again
- This avoids re-computation for the whole window. Add one → Remove one ✅


There are generally two categories of Sliding window problems:
- Fixed Size Sliding Window Problems
- Variable Size Sliding Window Problems